text: Area college football report for Oct. 10 Comment By From staff, wire reports The Independent By From staff, wire reports Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 11:31 PM By From staff, wire reports Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 11:31 PM Walsh wins double overtime thriller WALSH 39, FINDLAY 38 (2OT) Matt Mustaka caught a 2-point conversion pass from quarterback Reid Worstell in double overtime to give the Cavaliers their first victory of the season. The conversion came just seconds after Worstell tossed a 25-yard touchdown pass to Aaron Male. The Cavaliers then elected to go for the win. The play capped a 10-point comeback by Walsh. The Cavaliers trailed 24-14 in the third quarter. A touchdown run by Worstell and a 26-yard field goal by Michael Dudics with 5:56 left in the game forced overtime. Worstell finished the game 22-of-32 for 247 yards with two touchdowns and one interception. Aaron Male was the leading rusher for Walsh with 124 yards on 15 carries. Findlay was led by Daiquone Ford with 178 yards and a touchdown on 34 carries. NORTHERN MICHIGAN 41, MALONE 13 Four turnovers doomed Malone as they fell on the road Saturday. Malone lost two fumbles and threw two interceptions. The Pioneers fumbled six times total. Matt Blasiole led the offensive effort for the Pioneers as he had 131 yards and the lone touchdown on 28 carries. It was the ninth rushing touchdown of the season for Blasiole. Blasiole is the first Malone running back since Joseph Peters in 2009 to have that many rushing touchdowns in a season. Northern Michigan quarterback Shaye Brown was 15-for-18 for 185 yards and three touchdowns. AKRON 47, EASTERN MICHIGAN 21 At Ypsilianti, Michigan, Thomas Woodson threw four first-half TD passes, Conor Hundley ran for two scores and Akron capitalized on turnovers to beat Eastern Michigan. Woodson was 14 of 22 for 222 yards, with TD passes of 9 yards to Imani Davis, 22 and 39 yards to Jerome Lane and a 1-yarder to Josh McNeil. Lane’s first TD was set up by Austin Wolf’s recovery of a fumble on a kickoff and McNeil’s was set up by Zach Guiser’s interception of a pass by Brogan Roback. Andrew Hauser blocked a punt for a safety. The Zips (3-3, 1-1 Mid-American Conference) held the Eagles (1-5, 0-2) to 60 yards rushing in the first half and led 40-14 at halftime. Hundley gained 119 yards on 17 carries, with scoring runs of 29 and 5 yards. Lane had four catches for 104 yards. NO. 24 TOLEDO 38, KENT STATE 7 At Toledo, Terry Swanson ran for 161 yards and a touchdown and Kareem Hunt had two scores in leading No. 24 Toledo. Toledo got off to a shaky start, but remained undefeated at 5-0, 2-0 in the Mid-American Conference. Kent State is 2-4, 1-1. Swanson carried 16 times, while Hunt had 16 carries for 85 yards. Rockets quarterback Phillip Ely was 19 for 32 for 205 yards and two touchdowns.
